 frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":14,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":45,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Fishacre was born about 1245, in Devon, England, her father, Peter Fishacre, was 31 and her mother, Joan de Cornwall, was -11. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir Richard Hydon. She died on 28 March 1291, in England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1245–28 March 1291":"umbes 1245–28. märts 1291","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1272–1357":"1272–1357","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1258–1319":"1258–1319","about 1272":"umbes 1272","about October 1285":"umbes oktoober 1